---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const sodiumSrc = 'https://renalcarematters.com/guides/sodium-salt-reduction-ckd.html';
const potSrc = 'https://renalcarematters.com/guides/potassium-hyperkalemia-ckd.html';
const phosSrc = 'https://renalcarematters.com/guides/phosphorus-ckd.html';
---
<BaseLayout title="Eating well on dialysis" description="The three minerals that matter most on dialysis — salt, potassium and phosphorus — explained in plain language, with practical Filipino-food tips.">
  <article class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">
      <a href="/kidney-health" style="font-weight:700;text-decoration:none">← Kidney Health Hub</a>
      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Eating well on dialysis</h1>
      <p class="lead">Food is one of the biggest levers you control. Three minerals matter most — here's how to handle them.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from <a href={potSrc}>renalcarematters.com</a>.</p>

      <h2>1. Salt (sodium) — cut this first</h2>
      <p>The average Filipino eats <strong>5–6 grams of sodium a day</strong> — more than double the kidney
      target. Cutting salt is the single most effective diet change: it lowers your blood pressure, and it
      lowers your <strong>thirst</strong>, which makes your fluid limit far easier to keep. Go easy on
      patis, toyo, bagoong, instant noodles, processed and canned foods, and chips.
      (<a href={sodiumSrc}>More on salt →</a>)</p>

      <h2>2. Potassium — the dangerous one</h2>
      <p>Your heart needs potassium to beat, but only within a narrow range. On dialysis, potassium can
      build up between sessions — and when it climbs too high it can disturb the heart's rhythm
      <strong>without any warning</strong>. It rises most over the long weekend gap, so diet discipline on
      Saturday and Sunday matters most. Your team will advise which high-potassium foods (some fruits,
      vegetables and juices) to <strong>limit or prepare differently</strong>. (<a href={potSrc}>More on potassium →</a>)</p>

      <h2>3. Phosphorus — the hidden one</h2>
      <p>Extra phosphorus can't be cleared well on dialysis, and over time it <strong>weakens bones and
      hardens blood vessels</strong>. It hides in processed foods, colas and some dairy. Two habits help:
      choose fewer processed/“additive” foods, and — if you're prescribed <strong>phosphate binders</strong>
      — take them <em>with</em> your meals as directed. (<a href={phosSrc}>More on phosphorus →</a>)</p>

      <div class="notice"><strong>And fluid.</strong> What you drink counts too — see
      <a href="/kidney-health/fluid-and-weight">Fluid &amp; weight between sessions</a>.</div>

      <h2>You don't have to figure this out alone</h2>
      <p>Our <strong>renal dietitians</strong> build a plan around real Filipino food and your own
      preferences — practical guidance, not a lecture. Bring your questions to your next session.</p>

      <p style="margin-top:20px"><a href="/new-patients#request" class="btn btn--primary">Talk to our dietitian</a></p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top:22px;font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from
        renalcarematters.com (<a href={sodiumSrc}>sodium</a>, <a href={potSrc}>potassium</a>,
        <a href={phosSrc}>phosphorus</a>). Medically reviewed by a nephrologist. Educational only; not a
        substitute for consultation or a dietitian's advice.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
